cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we'll be continuing our look at the Precision 1@C Opening & Responses.

During the last session we looked at the requirements for the 1@C Opening, the negative, positive 4441 positive responses.

I'll be recapping the main points from that session again in a minute or so.

Tonight, the main 2 things we will be looking at in a bit more detail are two things I mentioned briefly last week, 4441 positive hands, and the Cambridge Heart Complex.


If you have not already done so, please have a look at the notes I have prepared on Precision Club bidding.

You can find these on: ^*h http://bbo.pigpen.org.uk/index.php ^*n

The notes on 1@C Openings can be found at ^*h http://bbo.pigpen.org.uk/1c.php^*n


You might want to have these on-screen in the background for reference during the session.|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Re - cap|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Okay, a brief recap of what we covered in the last session: The 1@C Opening takes care of ANY hand which contains more 16 or more HCP.

The only exception (in this system) are hands in the 16-23 point range with any 4441 distribution, which are opened with 2@D (which we'll cover NEXT week).

The 1@C Opening shows 16+ points.  It says absolutely nothing about the Club suit and must be alerted.

The opening is unconditionally FORCING for ONE round.  In the event of a 1@D Negative response, subsequent bidding is normally natural and non-forcing.

Any response other than 1@D is a "positive" which makes the sequence Game-forcing.

The 1@D response shows 0-7 points and is a "negative" response.

Subsequent bidding is natural and non-forcing, although the 1@C Opener is obliged to respond to the 1@D response.

If the 1@C Opener has an absolute rock-crusher of a hand, they can jump-shift over the 1@D Negative.

This makes the sequence game-forcing, but Opener should bear in mind that partner may have nothing at all, so this move normally shows 24+ points with a decent suit.

Once we start using Asking Bids, this jump-shift into a new suit over the 1@D negative response is the only way Opener can force an Asking Bid sequence over a negative.|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


bt||
nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Positive Responses|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The bids  1@H, 1@S, 1NT, 2@C and 2@D  are all positive responses showing 8+ points.

Show a 5-card Major before a 6-card or longer minor suit.

These responses are all game-forcing so although subsequent bidding is natural, it can be constructive with no need to jump to show extra strength.

Please note this: In this system we SWAP the 1@S and 1NT responses unless there is interference, so  

^c1@C - 1@S  ^fshows 8+ ^*bbalanced^*n     
^c1@C - 1NT  ^fshows 8+ with 5+ @s^*bSpades^*n@s.

5332 - shape hands almost always show a positive response in the long suit, especially if it is a Major.

Semi-balanced hands with a 5-card MINOR that are only marginal positives (8 - 10) will, as matter of course however, often use the 1@S response (^*bbalanced^*n 8+) because it is so much cheaper.

Ok, that recaps briefly what we covered last time apart from what I'll be covering in more detail tonight.

If you missed the last session or are still unsure of anything, check the notes on the website.

The Chat log and example hands from last week can be downloaded from the Precision Sessions page under the 

IAC Program page  -  ^*h http://bbo.pigpen.org.uk/IACProgram.php##Past^*n


