nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Cambridge Heart Complex|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Let's start off looking at the Cambridge Heart Complex in a little more detail.

As we've seen our opening 1NT Bid is  10 - 12  when not vulnerable and  13 - 15  when vulnerable, balanced intermediate hands of the "wrong" range being opened  1@D.

1@C - 1@D - 1NT  shows  16 - 18  balanced and the continuations are identical to those over an Opening 1NT, except that since responder is KNOWN to be in the  0 - 7  range, we tend not to use the jump-shift responses.

So what do we do with 19+ balanced hands? One of the problems with Standard American, 2/1, Acol etc is that very strong balanced hands are not properly catered for.

20 - 22  point hands can be opened  2NT  and 23+ balanced hands with 2@C, but these waste a lot of space, especially when responder has some values.

If you are lucky enough to pick up a 26+ point balanced hand, SAYC or 2/1 has no precise or space efficient way to show that range.


|fp|t-title|at|History|fp||at|^^^^|
at|Back in the 1970's, my younger brother and I came up with something called the Cambridge Heart Complex.  

(The name comes from the fact that Paul was living in Cambridge at the time and I was visiting him LOL) for showing 16+ balanced (or semi-balanced with a 5-card Minor) hands.


^*bMM:^*n  That would be the Cambridge in England, of course.^*n|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


qx|Camb2,wide|
nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Advantages|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  This has a multitude of advantages: 

^c@.   Balanced hands up to 29 HCP are catered for in sensible ranges (up to 33 HCP with the Complex Sys).

^c@.   This is accomplished without "losing" any other bids.

^c@.   Since@2 ALL 16+ balanced hands are opened with 1@C, we lose no bidding space when Responder has a POSITIVE rather than a Negative response.

^b@2We achieve this "precision" by making 1@C - 1@D - 1@H  a  TWO-WAY  bid, showing either ...

^c(1)   Any 16+ hand with 5+ Hearts (and without same length or longer Spades), or ...

^c(2)   19+ balanced or semi-balanced with a 5-card Minor.

Responder normally makes an automatic relay in 1@S.

There are exceptions, when you are  0 - 4  with a Lo-o-o-o-o-o-ng Minor (Bid 2@C or 2@D), or when you are  5 - 7,  with 5-card Hearts  ^*bAND^*n  an outside Singleton (Bid 1NT with a Minor suit singleton and 2@H with a Spade Singleton).

A long Spade suit is less of a problem, since you can transfer into it and leave Opener there if necessary, without the sequence getting too expensive.

