Depending on what the 1NT intervention shows:  Responder bids the cheapest 4-card MINOR they have, AS LONG AS it is NOT a suit that Opps have PROMISED.

So if 1NT shows "Both Majors or Both Minors", Opps have NOT specifically promised ANY particular suit, so Responder bids their cheapest 4-card Minor as a positive.

Clearly this will be indistinguishable from a 5-card Positive in that Minor, so Opener needs to be aware of the possibility of Responder only having a 4-card suit.

We've not changed the "minimum length" for Gamma in these sequences, so Responder just has to "lie" and treat their 4-card suit as a 5-card one.

If Responder cannot show a positive in a 4-card Minor, for whatever reason (eg: Opps have shown both Minors, or have shown one of the Minors and THAT is Responder's only 4-card Minor), then Responder either makes a trap Pass or a Double (showing 5 - 7), and later makes some kind of Impossible Negative response to show the suit below their singleton, or perhaps passes a re-opening double for penalties.

